<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-500-592  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 500 592.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Network World  June 4 1990 v7 n23 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>When is diverse network routing not really diverse? (multiplecarriers lease capacity on same fiber or separate fibers in sametrench)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wallace, Bob.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>True diversity in network routing is not easy to achieve, aslong-haul carrier fiber cuts have revealed.andP;  Carriers often leasecapacity on each other's networks, so that one fiber or multiplefibers in the same trench may be used by several differentcarriers.andP;  Many users who think they have route diversity becausethey do business with more than one carrier for service betweentwo points may be unpleasantly surprised by overlap.andP;  Somebusinesses find a partial solution by distributing their majornetwork artery commerce between major carriers, which are lesslikely to be trading capacity with other vendors.andP;  In an effort toprovide more diversity, more fiber is being laid for redundantroutes in 1990 than for new network routes.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     T1 CommunicationsDigital CommunicationsFiber OpticsCommunications EquipmentCommunications Service SuppliersNetwork ManagementRouting.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>